title: For Sale/Trade:  Marlin Model 2000 precision target rifle.
postcontent:
The 2000 series platform

Marlin firearms decided to punch out of their comfort level in the 1990s with a bolt-action single shot heavy target rifle. Designed to compete with entry-level Remington Model 40 and Anschutz target rifles, the new Marlin gun was unlike anything ever made by the company. Designed with a 22-inch heavy barrel with a recessed match-style crown and matched chamber, the rifle was embedded in a distinctive blue ISU standard stock of a fiberglass/Kevlar (Carbelite) combination with a high comb, stippled forearm, and pistol grip. The stock had an adjustable butt plate for length of pull. 
Accuracy of these series is superb. In a February 1996 Gun Tests article, they wrote the following, "The best the Marlin could do at 50 yards was 0.6-inch groups, which we shot with Eley Tenex. Three other ammo lots, CCI Green Tag Competition, Dynamit Nobel's RWS R50, and Lapua Dominator, averaged 0.7-inch groups. The 2000 didn't like Federal's Gold Medal Match rimfire ammo, shooting 0.9-inch groups."

title: For Sale:  FR8 Spanish Mauser    SOLD SOLD SOLD SOLD
postcontent:
I have for sale a FR8 Spanish Mauser (.308) 7.62x 51 Nato. Hard to find! Make offer.

The FR7 and FR8 were introduced in the 1950s when the Spanish military was already implementing the CETME automatic rifle, but did not yet have sufficient inventory to equip and train all troops. The rifles were made from existing stockpiles of Mauser bolt-action rifles, the FR-7 from the rifle model 1919 Santa Barbara and the FR-8 from the 1943 Santa Barbara carbine. They were adjusted to the new NATO calibre 7.62×51mm and, being of a suitably compact built, the FR 8 was used well into the 1970s by mounted Guardia Civil units in the Sierra Nevada. The flash hider was designed to be compatible with NATO-standard rifle grenades. The under-barrel tube, which resembles the gas cylinder found on automatic weapons, actually serves as the bayonet mount and as storage for cleaning gear. The rear sight is an elevation-adjustable rotary type with aperatures for 200 m (220 yd), 300 m (330 yd) and 400 m (440 yd), as well as an open "V" notch for 100 metres (110 yd). The front sight is elevation-adjustable via a special tool. Operation is identical to the standard Mauser design.

title: For Sale:  Extremely rare massive 18 gauge (16.8mm) German rifle
postcontent: this is a centerfire rifle made around 1890 in Merchigan, Loraine, which at that time was in southern Germany. it is a 16.8x55mm, or .660 caliber wich translates to exactly 18 gauge. the round in the pictures is a .30-06 for scale. it is the ONLY 18 gauge centerfire rifle known to exist in the collecting world. I have done hours of research on this gun, and coresponded with several colectors associations to try to find information, and no one has ever heard of or seen an 18 bore rifle. it was made for a shotting competition, popular in those days where a large wooden eagle is placed on a pole at a given distance, and whoever can shoot the most, or the last piece of it off wins. these guns are known to exist in very small numbers in 16 gauge, but this is the only one known to have been made in 18. it has a fully rifled octagon barrel and weighs a whopping 16.2 pounds. it functions perfectly, and has no damage or rust. the bore is clean and shinny. since it is an antique, I can ship it.
